that were trained

00:02:01.960 --> 00:02:06.340
to think very rigidly,
to quantify everything,

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:09.160
it's a big disadvantage when
you invest in the stock market.

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:11.260
So we're going to
start with that.

00:02:11.260 --> 00:02:15.190
And so as an engineer,
I was trained

00:02:15.190 --> 00:02:17.200
with a scientific education.

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:21.790
So we're trained to
develop a rational mind.

00:02:21.790 --> 00:02:24.520
You need to understand numbers.

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:25.960
And I think it's
a big advantage.

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:28.330
Because there's a lot
of financial belief

00:02:28.330 --> 00:02:31.150
that-- you know, people that
are trained in the finance

00:02:31.150 --> 00:02:35.270
business, I think they learn
things that, I believe,

00:02:35.270 --> 00:02:36.950
are not really scientific.

00:02:36.950 --> 00:02:40.240
And we don't need to
unlearn those things.

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:43.960
But at the same time, a
scientific education, I think,

00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:48.210
has some of disadvantages when
it comes to the stock market.

00:02:48.210 --> 00:02:51.920
We're trained to look at
past numbers on the belief

00:02:51.920 --> 00:02:55.040
that the future will be similar.

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:57.120
Humans, sometimes, they
don't behave like atoms.

00:02:57.120 --> 00:02:59.990
So you have to understand
that the financial world is

00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:01.650
a very strange world.

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:05.750
And when you train to
think very rigidly,

00:03:05.750 --> 00:03:08.820
it's hard, sometimes, to
understand what's happening.

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:12.570
And as a scientific, we're
trained not to judge,

00:03:12.570 --> 00:03:13.920
but to gather facts.

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:18.390
And judgment is a big part of
the stock investing process.

00:03:18.390 --> 00:03:22.230
And also, we're trained to
be very precise and right.

00:03:22.230 --> 00:03:26.100
But investing is about being
unprecise-- imprecise--

00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:29.580
and also accepting
that you will be wrong

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:32.130
30%, 35%, 40% of the time.

00:03:32.130 --> 00:03:35.190
And that's a good ratio.

00:03:35.190 --> 00:03:38.760
So I wanted just to put a quote
by one of the great engineers

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:40.110
of all time, Nikola Tesla.

00:03:40.110 --> 00:03:42.870
And he said that
"instinct is something

00:03:42.870 --> 00:03:44.310
that is important in science.

00:03:44.310 --> 00:03:46.170
It transcends knowledge."

00:03:46.170 --> 00:03:50.730
And I think that's a
very interesting quote.

00:03:50.730 --> 00:03:55.540
But at the same time, there's
a big difference between art,

00:03:55.540 --> 00:03:57.290
science, and alchemy.

00:03:57.290 --> 00:04:01.550
And you know, during
many centuries,

00:04:01.550 --> 00:04:04.950
alchemists tried to
change lead in gold.

00:04:04.950 --> 00:04:06.430
And that's not really science.

00:04:06.430 --> 00:04:11.220
And so this idea that I have a
great feeling about that stock,

00:04:11.220 --> 00:04:12.230
that's not really art.

00:04:12.230 --> 00:04:13.710
Neither it is investing.

00:04:13.710 --> 00:04:16.560
It's really just being lazy.

00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:20.550
So if you want to be an
artist in the investing world,

00:04:20.550 --> 00:04:23.460
well, you want to
master that art.

00:04:23.460 --> 00:04:26.580
So you want to first choose
an art that you really love.

00:04:26.580 --> 00:04:29.620
You want to study the
masters of that art.

00:04:29.620 --> 00:04:33.270
And also, it's important
that, as master paints,

00:04:33.270 --> 00:04:34.140
investor invests.

00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:38.130
So you want to be
active in your art.

00:04:38.130 --> 00:04:40.660
And you want, also, to
develop your own style,

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:46.090
have an independent mind, and
always strive for improvements.

00:04:46.090 --> 00:04:48.580
And I have this
quote by Woody Allen.

00:04:48.580 --> 00:04:51.070
And he said that "in order
to be a jazz musician,

00:04:51.070 --> 00:04:52.690
you have to listen to jazz.

00:04:52.690 --> 00:04:54.820
And it's an act of love."

00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:58.450
You listen to music not
because you want to learn it,

00:04:58.450 --> 00:04:59.980
but because you enjoy it.

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:05.380
And gradually, through kind
of a system of osmosis,

00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:08.830
it learn into you.

00:05:08.830 --> 00:05:11.370
I think any art that
you want to learn,

00:05:11.370 --> 00:05:14.360
you have to go to it
through an act of love.

00:05:16.950 --> 00:05:20.270
And I have this
quote by Jim Collins.

00:05:20.270 --> 00:05:23.830
And he said that "you can either
follow a paint-by-number kit

00:05:23.830 --> 00:05:25.710
approach to life,
or you can decide

00:05:25.710 --> 00:05:28.330
you want to create
your own masterpiece."

00:05:28.330 --> 00:05:34.039
And in the investing world,
if you want to be original,

00:05:34.039 --> 00:05:35.830
you have to accept
that, probably, you will

00:05:35.830 --> 00:05:37.580
be different from the others.

00:05:37.580 --> 00:05:42.820
And you'll probably have
to be eccentric, rash,

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:43.690
unconventional.

00:05:43.690 --> 00:05:46.202
And that's a quote by
John Maynard Keynes.

00:05:46.202 --> 00:05:48.660
He wrote a book called "The
State of Long-Term Expectation"

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:50.590
in 1936.

00:05:50.590 --> 00:05:54.100
And it is the long-term
investor that, in practice,

00:05:54.100 --> 00:05:56.420
will be very different
from the others,

00:05:56.420 --> 00:05:58.300
and probably criticized
at some point.

00:05:58.300 --> 00:06:01.210
Because "it is in the
essence of his behavior

00:06:01.210 --> 00:06:04.300
that he'll be eccentric, rash,
and unconventional in the eyes

00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:07.260
of the average opinion."

00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:09.810
That means that if you
want to obtain better

00:06:09.810 --> 00:06:11.910
results in the stock
market, you have

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:13.350
to be able to stand on your own.

00:06:13.350 --> 00:06:16.210
And you'll be different than
the typical crowd of investors.

00:06:16.210 --> 00:06:18.630
And that's sometimes
hard to-- it's fun

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:20.550
when you look at that picture.

00:06:20.550 --> 00:06:22.680
But it's sometimes
a little hard.

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:25.230
Because you have to
be different and have,

00:06:25.230 --> 00:06:28.890
sometimes, a very contrarian
opinion than the average

00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:33.070
view on the-- either a stock
or the stock market in general.

00:06:33.070 --> 00:06:35.100
So let's look at the
results of money managers

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:37.470
in general in our
investing world.

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:42.270
So that's the normal bell
curve of the typical results

00:06:42.270 --> 00:06:43.800
as investors.

00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:46.530
And this line here
is the S&amp;P 500.

00:06:46.530 --> 00:06:49.560
And the S&amp;P 500 is
not right in middle

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:54.060
for the very simple reason
that managers charge fees.

00:06:54.060 --> 00:06:59.750
So from scratch, they start
from, probably, 1% or 2%

00:06:59.750 --> 00:07:01.210
behind the S&amp;P 500.

00:07:01.210 --> 00:07:05.640
So just because of that,
the S&amp;P 500 probably

00:07:05.640 --> 00:07:08.980
beats out 85% of investors.

00:07:08.980 --> 00:07:13.240
So you want, always,
to think what not to do

00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:15.140
if you want to beat the index.

00:07:15.140 --> 00:07:19.250
So if you want to beat
the normal distribution,

00:07:19.250 --> 00:07:20.750
what do you want not to do?

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:24.080
Well, if you think the
same way as most investors,

00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:26.240
and you have the
same time horizon,

00:07:26.240 --> 00:07:28.830
you'll probably end up
with the same results.

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:32.000
So also, if you own
lots of companies,

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.790
it's very hard to
differ from the index.

00:07:34.790 --> 00:07:38.300
And I would add to that, if
you believe that you're smarter

00:07:38.300 --> 00:07:41.760
than the others, and you can
predict the stock market,

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:45.490
I think it's a road to failure.

00:07:45.490 --> 00:07:49.120
So what do you want to do if you
want to beat the normal curve?

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:53.250
Well, so far, the
last 24 years, we've

00:07:53.250 --> 00:07:56.480
probably been in the
top 1% of investors.

00:07:56.480 --> 00:08:00.420
So let's hope it's not
pure luck and that we

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:03.090
do have an investment
approach that

00:08:03.090 --> 00:08:05.020
helps out to beat the index.

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:07.030
So what do we do?

00:08:07.030 --> 00:08:09.420
We try to think for ourself.

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:14.280
We try to own very
few selected companies

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:16.250
and develop the right
behaviors, which

00:08:16.250 --> 00:08:17.550
I'll go through a little later.

00:08:17.550 --> 00:08:22.240
But these are rationality,
humility, and patience.

00:08:22.240 --> 00:08:24.970
So perhaps we can go to our
stock selection process.

00:08:24.970 --> 00:08:27.280
So that's the
science part of it.

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:30.540
So we start with the financial
strength of the companies.

00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:33.090
We want companies that have
higher return on capital, that

00:08:33.090 --> 00:08:35.940
have grown their earnings
per share, that also,

00:08:35.940 --> 00:08:38.100
at the same time, have
a strong balance sheet.

00:08:38.100 --> 00:08:40.080
So the debt to profit
ratio, usually you

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:43.289
would want something like
less than four times.

00:08:43.289 --> 00:08:45.830
And we want a business
model that is very solid.

00:08:45.830 --> 00:08:48.810
So we want companies that
are market leaders, that

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:52.290
have competitive advantage,
and low cyclicality.

00:08:52.290 --> 00:08:54.550
And a competitive advantage
is very important.

00:08:54.550 --> 00:08:58.230
And I'll go back to that
point a little later.

00:08:58.230 --> 00:09:01.590
The management
team-- so we want,

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:05.760
you know, the CEO, the CFO,
the high management team,

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:08.550
to own lots of shares
in the company.

00:09:08.550 --> 00:09:10.400
So you want a high
level of ownership,

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:13.510
so they're really in
the same boat as we are.

00:09:13.510 --> 00:09:18.720
We want managers that have good
capital allocation skills, they

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:21.030
make constructive
acquisitions, and you know,

00:09:21.030 --> 00:09:24.930
they really think long-term
when they make investments.

00:09:24.930 --> 00:09:27.210
And then we have
market valuation.

00:09:27.210 --> 00:09:31.380
So we want to stock that
we'll purchase at a level

00:09:31.380 --> 00:09:34.380
that we can double our
money over five years, which

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:37.020
is something like
15% annual return.

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:40.410
So without being very precise--

00:09:40.410 --> 00:09:42.020
because we know
that, probably, it's

00:09:42.020 --> 00:09:44.610
an illusion when you
try to be too precise--

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:47.760
we try to have a view of
what we think the company can

00:09:47.760 --> 00:09:49.080
earn in five years.

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:52.560
And it's going to help us to
modelize what kind of valuation

00:09:52.560 --> 00:09:56.584
we can expect during that time.

00:09:56.584 --> 00:09:58.680
A few words about art--

00:09:58.680 --> 00:10:03.750
first, I want to say that
and beauty are, in some ways,

00:10:03.750 --> 00:10:04.950
interrelated.

00:10:04.950 --> 00:10:08.100
And you know, very few money
managers talk about beauty,

00:10:08.100 --> 00:10:09.540
but I think it's important.

00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:11.460
How do you define beauty
in the investment?

00:10:11.460 --> 00:10:15.810
Well, we say that beauty,
usually, to our eyes,

00:10:15.810 --> 00:10:17.310
is something that is rare.

00:10:17.310 --> 00:10:19.050
We usually find
something beautiful

00:10:19.050 --> 00:10:22.830
when it's something
that we seldom see.

00:10:22.830 --> 00:10:27.870
And something that is
unique, we never see.

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:31.650
So it's really the rarest
of all the beauties.

00:10:31.650 --> 00:10:34.470
And I always-- sometimes,
when I read an annual report

00:10:34.470 --> 00:10:36.420
and look at the
numbers, when I have

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:40.920
these feelings that, wow,
this is a beautiful company,

00:10:40.920 --> 00:10:42.670
it returns high
return on capital,

00:10:42.670 --> 00:10:46.640
it has much better margin than
their competitors, you know,

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:50.100
there's something that
lights up in my mind.

00:10:50.100 --> 00:10:54.270
So what you want is to find
what I call masterpieces.

00:10:54.270 --> 00:10:57.390
And they have one quality,
they're rare and unique.

00:10:57.390 --> 00:11:00.000
So I've taken some
example in the art world--

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.780
so the "Mona Lisa," a Rothko
painting, a Vincent van Gogh

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:05.350
painting.

00:11:05.350 --> 00:11:07.980
And if you want to take
some example of business

00:11:07.980 --> 00:11:10.680
masterpieces, well, I've
gone through the history

00:11:10.680 --> 00:11:13.530
of the capitalist
world, mostly in the US.

00:11:13.530 --> 00:11:17.010
And we can start with, probably,
one of the first technology

00:11:17.010 --> 00:11:20.730
company in the 1880s
called National Cash

00:11:20.730 --> 00:11:22.820
Register, that you've
probably heard about.

00:11:22.820 --> 00:11:25.260
Hewlett-Packard,
that, many years ago,

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:32.250
was a very innovative company,
Apple, IKEA, T.J.Maxx, Geico,

00:11:32.250 --> 00:11:36.130
the insurance company owned by
Berkshire, "Washington Post,"

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:39.420
H&amp;R Block, Dun &amp;
Bradstreet, Gilette,

00:11:39.420 --> 00:11:42.210
McDonald's, Starbucks, I
think all these companies--

00:11:42.210 --> 00:11:43.890
and we could
certainly add Google

00:11:43.890 --> 00:11:46.860
to that lot-- these are
business masterpieces.

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:49.680
So you want to study
those kind of businesses

00:11:49.680 --> 00:11:52.830
and see, what do they
have that was so unique.

00:11:52.830 --> 00:11:55.725
And usually, the uniqueness,
in either their product,

00:11:55.725 --> 00:11:57.830
or their service,
or the culture,

00:11:57.830 --> 00:12:00.290
is the equivalent of
having a moat that

00:12:00.290 --> 00:12:03.600
protects your castle,
your enconomic castle,

00:12:03.600 --> 00:12:06.610
from invaders, which
are competitors.

00:12:06.610 --> 00:12:08.190
So that's the key thing.

00:12:08.190 --> 00:12:11.900
You want to own a moat with
lots of crocodiles and piranhas

00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:18.240
in it so competitors don't
want to come near your castle.

00:12:18.240 --> 00:12:23.490
So if we could resume kind of
what we look for in a company,

00:12:23.490 --> 00:12:25.860
it's really three things--

00:12:25.860 --> 00:12:29.520
the competitive advantages,
which we could say

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:33.690
is the artistic part of that,
the financial strength, which

00:12:33.690 --> 00:12:36.700
is really the science part,
and the management team.

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:39.220
And this is where
judgment comes into play.

00:12:39.220 --> 00:12:42.090
It's very important to be
able to judge management.

00:12:42.090 --> 00:12:44.730
And you know, that's kind
of a subjective thing when

00:12:44.730 --> 00:12:46.800
you're talking about judgment.

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:48.540
But you know, I always say--

00:12:48.540 --> 00:12:51.750
I have this phrase that,
when you meet management,

00:12:51.750 --> 00:12:56.450
you ask yourself, would I like
this man to marry my daughter.

00:12:56.450 --> 00:12:59.190
And if their answer
is yes, it's probably

00:12:59.190 --> 00:13:01.880
a good man to be partner with.

00:13:01.880 --> 00:13:05.630
So we end up with something
like 125 stocks that

00:13:05.630 --> 00:13:07.130
fits our criterias.

00:13:07.130 --> 00:13:09.950
And the one that we do
buy for the portfolio

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:12.080
are the ones that
fit our criterias

00:13:12.080 --> 00:13:15.260
in terms of market valuation--
if we can buy at a price,

00:13:15.260 --> 00:13:17.780
today, that we hope
we can earn something

00:13:17.780 --> 00:13:21.220
like 14% going forward, yearly.

00:13:21.220 --> 00:13:25.590
So perhaps, just
take a few examples

00:13:25.590 --> 00:13:27.120
to illustrate our approach.

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:30.810
Well, one company I think is
very unique is Walt Disney.

00:13:30.810 --> 00:13:32.640
They have great brand name.

00:13:32.640 --> 00:13:35.105
They own the Star
Wars franchise.

00:13:35.105 --> 00:13:38.880
They own, of course, all those
historical stars like Mickey

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:40.620
Mouse and Winnie the Pooh.

00:13:40.620 --> 00:13:43.240
And they bought Marvel
a few years back.

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:46.070
And you know, I always
say that Mickey Mouse

00:13:46.070 --> 00:13:48.690
has three great qualities.

00:13:48.690 --> 00:13:53.410
First, he is highly popular
and known all around the world.

00:13:53.410 --> 00:13:55.260
Second, he is immortal.

00:13:55.260 --> 00:13:57.360
And the third, he has no agent.

00:13:57.360 --> 00:13:59.760
So you really own your star.

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:03.690
And that's a great
thing for Disney.

00:14:03.690 --> 00:14:06.060
And the uniqueness of
business model of Disney

00:14:06.060 --> 00:14:12.590
is that they have these big
movie blockbusters, like

00:14:12.590 --> 00:14:14.830
"Alice in Wonderland" in 1951.

00:14:14.830 --> 00:14:18.460
And then, 50 years later,
they can redo a new version

00:14:18.460 --> 00:14:21.010
and make money again
with the same name.

00:14:21.010 --> 00:14:23.710
And they did that recently
with "The Jungle Book."

00:14:23.710 --> 00:14:26.740
They released the first
animated version 1967,

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:29.270
and they did a real
live version last year,

00:14:29.270 --> 00:14:30.910
which was also a big success.

00:14:30.910 --> 00:14:33.430
So it's kind like
opening an oil field

00:14:33.430 --> 00:14:35.020
where you take all the oil.

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:36.940
And 50 years later, you
go back to the field,

00:14:36.940 --> 00:14:40.170
and there's even more
new oil to take out.

00:14:40.170 --> 00:14:42.740
And you don't need to
spend money on capital

00:14:42.740 --> 00:14:46.270
and pay people to
guard you field.

00:14:46.270 --> 00:14:49.860
It's really an extraordinary
business model.

00:14:49.860 --> 00:14:54.110
We bought that stock probably
11, 12 years ago, I think,

00:14:54.110 --> 00:14:55.070
in 2005.

00:14:55.070 --> 00:14:57.110
We paid about $24.

00:14:57.110 --> 00:15:00.830
And it was the day that
Bob Iger was named CEO.

00:15:00.830 --> 00:15:02.660
And we've owned it since then.

00:15:02.660 --> 00:15:05.900
So there was a period when
the stock did not do much.

00:15:05.900 --> 00:15:09.420
As you can see, for four years,
the stock didn't do very well.

00:15:09.420 --> 00:15:11.300
But earnings kept growing.

00:15:11.300 --> 00:15:12.380
And we were patient.

00:15:12.380 --> 00:15:16.010
And if you look over the 12
years we've owned the stock,

00:15:16.010 --> 00:15:18.950
earnings have grown
about 13% annually.

00:15:18.950 --> 00:15:21.560
And in the end, the stock
has more than quadrupled.

00:15:21.560 --> 00:15:29.400
So if you're patient, and
companies grew their value,

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:31.230
eventually the
stock will follow.

00:15:31.230 --> 00:15:33.630
I want to take another
example of a stock that's been

00:15:33.630 --> 00:15:36.030
a while in portfolio, CarMax.

00:15:36.030 --> 00:15:38.470
It's been, 10 years,
in the portfolio.

00:15:38.470 --> 00:15:43.610
And as you can see, earnings per
share have grown at about 16%

00:15:43.610 --> 00:15:46.830
annually since we
bought it in 2007.

00:15:46.830 --> 00:15:50.350
And the stock has
done very similar,

00:15:50.350 --> 00:15:53.500
even though the P/E ratio is
a little lower today than when

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:54.840
we first bought it.

00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:57.450
We first bought it
in the summer 2007.

00:15:57.450 --> 00:16:02.370
At that time, the P/E
ratio was about 24 times.

00:16:02.370 --> 00:16:05.340
We bought more shares
in 2011 at 14 times,

00:16:05.340 --> 00:16:08.160
and more shares in 2016,
again, at 14 times.

00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:11.230
And today the stock is
above 18 times earnings.

00:16:11.230 --> 00:16:13.980
So even though the
P/E ratio has been

00:16:13.980 --> 00:16:17.220
reduced a bit over the years,
the stock has done pretty well.

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:21.780
It's done about 13% annually
even though earnings

00:16:21.780 --> 00:16:24.060
grew about 16% annually.

00:16:24.060 --> 00:16:27.710
And that's about 5%
better than the S&amp;P 500.

00:16:27.710 --> 00:16:29.645
Dividend included,
it has down about 8%

00:16:29.645 --> 00:16:31.680
annually over the last decade.

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:35.680
So it's been a good investment.

00:16:35.680 --> 00:16:38.310
I want to say a few words
about a competitive advantage.

00:16:38.310 --> 00:16:42.450
As investors at Giverny, what
kind of competitive advantage

00:16:42.450 --> 00:16:43.230
can we have?

00:16:43.230 --> 00:16:48.930
Well, first, I think it's three
things, patience, humility,

00:16:48.930 --> 00:16:51.830
and rationality.

00:16:51.830 --> 00:16:56.470
Humility-- I think we
do believe that it's

00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:59.230
impossible to predict
macroeconomic events.

00:16:59.230 --> 00:17:02.220
So we don't try to predict them.

00:17:02.220 --> 00:17:06.280
Also, one key
element is to focus

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:08.859
on your circle of
competence and to know where

00:17:08.859 --> 00:17:11.410
the limit of that circle is.

00:17:11.410 --> 00:17:14.230
And thirdly, we want to
recognize our mistakes

00:17:14.230 --> 00:17:17.890
when we do them and always try
to improve our stock selection

00:17:17.890 --> 00:17:19.790
process.

00:17:19.790 --> 00:17:22.240
A few words on the
timing of purchases--

00:17:22.240 --> 00:17:26.000
Woody Allen said that 80%
of success is showing up.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.550
And so that's one
of the main reasons

00:17:28.550 --> 00:17:30.890
we always want to be
invested in the stock market.

00:17:30.890 --> 00:17:34.120
Because we believe that
owning great companies,

00:17:34.120 --> 00:17:35.840
not trying to predict
the stock market,

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:39.350
is the key thing
to be able to beat

00:17:39.350 --> 00:17:41.150
the index over the long run.

00:17:41.150 --> 00:17:44.270
And by always striving
for improvement,

00:17:44.270 --> 00:17:47.420
we try to study our
mistakes in details.

00:17:47.420 --> 00:17:49.910
So each year, on
an annual letter,

00:17:49.910 --> 00:17:53.750
we have this yearly metals that
we give to our best mistakes.

00:17:53.750 --> 00:17:57.110
And it's a very popular
part of our annual letter.

00:17:57.110 --> 00:18:00.830
I don't know why, because
it's very painful.

00:18:00.830 --> 00:18:03.320
But I think that's
very important

00:18:03.320 --> 00:18:06.410
if you want to continue
to improve yourself.

00:18:06.410 --> 00:18:08.290
A few words on rationality--

00:18:08.290 --> 00:18:10.220
we try not to be
affected when others

00:18:10.220 --> 00:18:12.170
make more money
than us in stocks,

00:18:12.170 --> 00:18:14.660
because there's always fads.

00:18:14.660 --> 00:18:16.400
And you know, we
don't get into fads.

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:20.390
So sometimes we'll be
different from what's

00:18:20.390 --> 00:18:23.520
going on in the very popular
part of the stock market.

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:26.420
But you know, we try to
be rational and say, well,

00:18:26.420 --> 00:18:27.830
if we don't really
understand it,

00:18:27.830 --> 00:18:33.200
if we don't think that's a good
area where our capital should

00:18:33.200 --> 00:18:36.000
be invested, we just
stay away from it.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.340
And we try to be impervious
to the stock market

00:18:38.340 --> 00:18:39.780
quotation in the short run.

00:18:39.780 --> 00:18:41.780
So it takes a lot
of rationality,

00:18:41.780 --> 00:18:44.610
because the stock market
can be very, very volatile.

00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:51.110
So we try to always be
calm and try to always

00:18:51.110 --> 00:18:54.870
have the eye on the long-term
horizons of the company we

00:18:54.870 --> 00:18:56.030
purchase.

00:18:56.030 --> 00:18:58.640
And we accept that we
don't know the future.

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:03.320
And we try to focus
on part of the process

00:19:03.320 --> 00:19:04.820
that we can control.

00:19:04.820 --> 00:19:08.120
It's really, like I said, to
look for companies that we

00:19:08.120 --> 00:19:10.100
understand, that we
believe, that have

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:12.050
a competitive advantage.

00:19:12.050 --> 00:19:14.990
And you know, we accept that you
don't know exactly how things

00:19:14.990 --> 00:19:16.370
will work out.

00:19:16.370 --> 00:19:19.910
But you know, if you own great
companies with great managers,

00:19:19.910 --> 00:19:22.860
eventually you should be OK.

00:19:22.860 --> 00:19:26.910
And that comes up to something
we put out a few years back.

00:19:26.910 --> 00:19:29.100
I call it the rule of three.

00:19:29.100 --> 00:19:32.460
It's really to accept that, one
year out of three, the stock

00:19:32.460 --> 00:19:35.280
markets will decline
about 10% or more.

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:39.300
One stock purchase out of three
will not perform as expected.

00:19:39.300 --> 00:19:42.490
And one year out of three,
you'll underperform the index.

00:19:42.490 --> 00:19:45.300
And the best managers
usually underperform

00:19:45.300 --> 00:19:46.660
one year out of three.

00:19:46.660 --> 00:19:50.850
So it's still a very ambitious
rule, a group of rules.

00:19:50.850 --> 00:19:54.870
But if you accept that
from the start, when you'll

00:19:54.870 --> 00:19:57.570
have some bad years on
some bad investments,

00:19:57.570 --> 00:19:59.670
you'll be better
prepared psychologically

00:19:59.670 --> 00:20:02.580
to deal with that.

00:20:02.580 --> 00:20:04.940
And a few words on
patience-- well,

00:20:04.940 --> 00:20:07.840
I have this saying that
"patience is not the ability

00:20:07.840 --> 00:20:11.650
to wait, but the ability to keep
a good attitude while waiting."

00:20:11.650 --> 00:20:14.710
So what's the good attitude
in the investment world?

00:20:14.710 --> 00:20:17.794
It's really to focus on what's
happening in the company,

00:20:17.794 --> 00:20:19.210
not what's happening
to the stock.

00:20:19.210 --> 00:20:22.100
And that's sometimes
a hard thing to do.

00:20:22.100 --> 00:20:24.730
But if you go back to
the example of CarMax,

00:20:24.730 --> 00:20:26.560
CarMax stock, over
the last decade,

00:20:26.560 --> 00:20:27.560
has been quite volatile.

00:20:27.560 --> 00:20:30.490
It went down 25% a few times.

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:33.880
But if you look at the
earnings over those 10 years,

00:20:33.880 --> 00:20:35.870
it's been a pretty
stable business.

00:20:35.870 --> 00:20:37.810
So if you just focus
on what's happened

00:20:37.810 --> 00:20:40.780
to CarMax over
the last 10 years,

00:20:40.780 --> 00:20:44.650
I think, besides 2009,
earnings went up every year.

00:20:44.650 --> 00:20:48.340
And it grew earnings by
more than 16% annually.

00:20:48.340 --> 00:20:52.120
So just focus on that, and
forget about the stock price

00:20:52.120 --> 00:20:55.770
movements, you'll be OK.

00:20:55.770 --> 00:20:58.780
But I want to say another
word about patience.

00:20:58.780 --> 00:21:01.180
That's not the same
thing as being stubborn.

00:21:01.180 --> 00:21:05.440
And sometimes we fail to
recognize mistakes we make.

00:21:05.440 --> 00:21:09.250
So I like to think
about the analogy of,

00:21:09.250 --> 00:21:12.550
how do you get a
frog to be cooked.

00:21:12.550 --> 00:21:16.570
If you put it in boiling water,
it will jump out of the bowl.

00:21:16.570 --> 00:21:20.050
So what you do, you
put it on mild water

00:21:20.050 --> 00:21:22.100
and slowly increase
the temperature.

00:21:22.100 --> 00:21:23.830
And you know, the
frog won't get out.

00:21:23.830 --> 00:21:25.780
Because you always
think, well, things

00:21:25.780 --> 00:21:29.960
are getting a little hotter, but
they'll cool down eventually.

00:21:29.960 --> 00:21:33.190
And you know, it never cools
down and eventually get cooked.

00:21:33.190 --> 00:21:36.280
So what you want is
not to buy a stock

00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:39.440
and, you know, earnings
are a little disappointing,

00:21:39.440 --> 00:21:42.240
the fundamentals start to
deteriorate, the stock go down.

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:44.050
But you don't want
to sell at a loss.

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:49.510
So when investment
doesn't work very well,

00:21:49.510 --> 00:21:53.170
I try to focus on what's
happening to the company

00:21:53.170 --> 00:21:57.580
to be sure that I'm not
getting cooked like a frog.

00:21:57.580 --> 00:21:59.700
And that's really important.

00:21:59.700 --> 00:22:02.380
And there's a big
difference in knowing

00:22:02.380 --> 00:22:06.880
when to keep your shares because
the fundamentals warrant it,

00:22:06.880 --> 00:22:08.950
and recognize you
made a mistake,

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:11.260
and just get out of that stock.

00:22:11.260 --> 00:22:14.200
And that's a big
difference between being

00:22:14.200 --> 00:22:17.660
patient and stubborn.

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:21.380
So to summarize
what differentiates

00:22:21.380 --> 00:22:26.120
an artistic investor, I would
say the conventional investor,

00:22:26.120 --> 00:22:28.370
the typical investor
in the stock market,

00:22:28.370 --> 00:22:31.070
either professional
or amateur, it's

00:22:31.070 --> 00:22:33.890
really the focus
on market quotes.

00:22:33.890 --> 00:22:35.862
They are short-term oriented.

00:22:35.862 --> 00:22:37.320
They have an opinion
on everything,

00:22:37.320 --> 00:22:40.280
and they try to predict
when to buy stocks.

00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:43.640
And they cannot
resist the latest fad.

00:22:43.640 --> 00:22:46.580
So I would say the
unconventional investor,

00:22:46.580 --> 00:22:49.630
while he focuses
on intrinsic value,

00:22:49.630 --> 00:22:52.010
he has a long-term horizon.

00:22:52.010 --> 00:22:55.340
He's agnostic about many,
many things, including

00:22:55.340 --> 00:22:58.860
where the stock market will be
in a few weeks or a few months.

00:22:58.860 --> 00:23:02.510
And at the same time, he doesn't
try to predict when to buy,

00:23:02.510 --> 00:23:05.210
but the focuses
more on what to buy.

00:23:05.210 --> 00:23:09.410
And I would say the right
verb is what to own.

00:23:09.410 --> 00:23:13.620
And of course, he resists the
fans and the popular beliefs.

00:23:13.620 --> 00:23:16.370
And it's easy to write
in a presentation,

00:23:16.370 --> 00:23:18.230
but it's harder
on the day-to-day

00:23:18.230 --> 00:23:21.150
to resist what's
been very popular.

00:23:21.150 --> 00:23:24.320
So that takes a lot of
independence of thought,

00:23:24.320 --> 00:23:26.010
I believe.

00:23:26.010 --> 00:23:30.570
So a wise investor must be able
to kind of balance many things.

00:23:30.570 --> 00:23:33.210
So I talked about
the love for the art.

00:23:33.210 --> 00:23:36.060
But at the same time, you
want to be very rational.

00:23:36.060 --> 00:23:38.680
You don't want to fall
in love with stocks.

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:41.220
You want us always be rational.

00:23:41.220 --> 00:23:44.860
You want to have a very
large field of knowledge

00:23:44.860 --> 00:23:47.470
and look at many,
many companies.

00:23:47.470 --> 00:23:49.500
But at the same time,
you want to focus

00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:51.510
on your circle of competence.

00:23:51.510 --> 00:23:53.137
You want to be open-minded.

00:23:53.137 --> 00:23:54.720
But at the same time,
you have to have

00:23:54.720 --> 00:23:56.350
independence of thoughts.

00:23:56.350 --> 00:23:59.560
You want to be able
to value the business.

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:02.850
But at the same, time, like
I said in this presentation,

00:24:02.850 --> 00:24:05.090
you want to be able to
go beyond the numbers.

00:24:05.090 --> 00:24:06.390
So it's just not numbers.

00:24:06.390 --> 00:24:08.970
If it was just
numbers, mathematicians

00:24:08.970 --> 00:24:10.750
would all the billionaires.

00:24:10.750 --> 00:24:14.170
So of course, it takes
a little more than that.

00:24:14.170 --> 00:24:15.390
You have to have patience.

00:24:15.390 --> 00:24:18.600
But at the same time, you don't
want to get cooked like a frog.

00:24:18.600 --> 00:24:20.729
And finally, you
want discipline,

00:24:20.729 --> 00:24:22.520
but you want to be able
to break the rules.

00:24:22.520 --> 00:24:25.260
So I always say
that the discipline

00:24:25.260 --> 00:24:28.050
is to follow your
own rules, but wisdom

00:24:28.050 --> 00:24:29.850
is to know when to
break your own rules.

00:24:29.850 --> 00:24:33.000
So sometimes we've bought
some stock that didn't really

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:34.830
fit our criterias.

00:24:34.830 --> 00:24:37.770
But you know, we made a
judgment call that we believe,

00:24:37.770 --> 00:24:39.870
most of the time,
either the business

00:24:39.870 --> 00:24:42.420
has, really, something
special or the management

00:24:42.420 --> 00:24:46.410
has, really, something
special, or ideally, both.

00:24:46.410 --> 00:24:49.264
So finally, to summarize
in one sentence,

00:24:49.264 --> 00:24:51.055
"To obtain better
results than the others,"

00:24:51.055 --> 00:24:53.220
I would quote John Templeton.

00:24:53.220 --> 00:24:55.260
He said that "you have
to do something different

00:24:55.260 --> 00:24:56.770
from the others."

00:24:56.770 --> 00:24:59.350
And at Giverny Capital,
what do we do differently?

00:24:59.350 --> 00:25:01.840
Well, first, we
think independently.

00:25:01.840 --> 00:25:04.470
We own very few
selected companies.

00:25:04.470 --> 00:25:06.750
We have a very
long-term horizon.

00:25:06.750 --> 00:25:10.890
I mean, I think, on average,
we own our stocks seven years.

00:25:10.890 --> 00:25:14.200
And the typical investor on
Wall Street's at seven months.

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:18.990
So that's kind of
a 12-to-1 ratio.

00:25:18.990 --> 00:25:22.230
And also, we try to develop
the right behaviors.

00:25:22.230 --> 00:25:26.600
We want to be rational,
humble, and patient.

00:25:26.600 --> 00:25:29.185
So that concludes
the presentation.

00:25:29.185 --> 00:25:30.060
