Berkshire or Markel,

00:38:44.210 --> 00:38:47.960
probably a price to
book is a better--

00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:49.430
it's not perfect,
but it's probably

00:38:49.430 --> 00:38:50.620
a better-- way to value.

00:38:50.620 --> 00:38:53.360
And you use a ratio.

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:58.940
I think, for both companies,
1.5 or 1.6 times book value

00:38:58.940 --> 00:39:00.170
would make sense.

00:39:00.170 --> 00:39:03.270
Because that's the
nature of their business,

00:39:03.270 --> 00:39:05.450
that the earnings
are more erratic.

00:39:05.450 --> 00:39:08.675
So you have to value
them some other way.

00:39:08.675 --> 00:39:12.162
So you have to adapt to the
business model of the business.

00:39:12.162 --> 00:39:14.120
SPEAKER 1: Francois, we
had one of our guests--

00:39:14.120 --> 00:39:16.162
they brought up a very
interesting concept.

00:39:16.162 --> 00:39:18.620
They said, you know, you look
at all these great companies,

00:39:18.620 --> 00:39:21.830
and you recognize
that there is a moat.

00:39:21.830 --> 00:39:24.320
And you know, over the
past 10 or 15 years,

00:39:24.320 --> 00:39:26.540
they've displayed
that in their numbers.

00:39:26.540 --> 00:39:28.970
And then you sit back
and ask yourself,

00:39:28.970 --> 00:39:32.770
the future may not necessarily
be identical to the past.

00:39:32.770 --> 00:39:36.710
So they said what really matters
is that the moat be growing.

00:39:36.710 --> 00:39:39.780
It doesn't matter whether
it's small or big.

00:39:39.780 --> 00:39:42.500
So how do you
think about growing

00:39:42.500 --> 00:39:46.900
moats, or emergent moats,
versus established moats?

00:39:46.900 --> 00:39:49.960
FRANCOIS ROCHON: That's very
hard, because moats always

00:39:49.960 --> 00:39:50.880
keep changing.

00:39:50.880 --> 00:39:56.230
And I remember, a few
years back, Charlie Munger

00:39:56.230 --> 00:39:57.640
said that--

00:39:57.640 --> 00:40:01.360
I asked a question to
Charlie about moats

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:04.450
and all those great
companies that seem

00:40:04.450 --> 00:40:07.690
to see their moat shrinking.

00:40:07.690 --> 00:40:10.570
And he said, well, I
know all those moats are

00:40:10.570 --> 00:40:12.540
getting filled with sand.

00:40:12.540 --> 00:40:16.920
And so I asked
him, which company

00:40:16.920 --> 00:40:19.290
do you think has
an expanding moat?

00:40:19.290 --> 00:40:21.160
And that was six
years, seven years ago.

00:40:21.160 --> 00:40:22.052
And he said, Google.

00:40:22.052 --> 00:40:23.010
SPEAKER 1: Interesting.

00:40:23.010 --> 00:40:26.740
FRANCOIS ROCHON: I think
that's an incredible company.

00:40:26.740 --> 00:40:30.660
And I remember thinking, well,
I knew about Google, of course.

00:40:30.660 --> 00:40:34.280
But I said, well, I should
take a new look at it.

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:39.090
And we bought shares in
2011 after that comment.

00:40:39.090 --> 00:40:40.920
So we were lucky.

00:40:40.920 --> 00:40:44.190
Because at that time, the
P/E ratio was 15 times.

00:40:44.190 --> 00:40:46.620
So if it would have been
a few points higher,

00:40:46.620 --> 00:40:51.930
we probably would have passed
and missed an increase of 400%

00:40:51.930 --> 00:40:52.860
since then.

00:40:52.860 --> 00:40:57.150
So there's always new
companies with moats.

00:40:57.150 --> 00:40:59.460
Some are expanding,
some our shrinking.

00:40:59.460 --> 00:41:01.650
So we have to
follow that closely.

00:41:01.650 --> 00:41:05.040
But if I had to
choose one criteria

00:41:05.040 --> 00:41:09.230
to help me decide what's
the direction of the moat,

00:41:09.230 --> 00:41:10.570
it's the managers.

00:41:10.570 --> 00:41:14.380
I mean, those moats are
not built by angels.

00:41:14.380 --> 00:41:15.650
They're built by human beings.

00:41:15.650 --> 00:41:19.660
So what makes a
moat grow, I think,

00:41:19.660 --> 00:41:23.370
is something in the
culture of the company.

00:41:23.370 --> 00:41:26.670
And those things doesn't
come from thin air.

00:41:26.670 --> 00:41:30.040
It comes from the top management
that builds that culture.

00:41:30.040 --> 00:41:33.760
And then it translates into
a moat, and then high return

00:41:33.760 --> 00:41:36.950
on equity for the shareholders.

00:41:36.950 --> 00:41:39.400
SPEAKER 1: So when you look
at the high returns of equity

00:41:39.400 --> 00:41:41.260
over the last 10
years, do you say

00:41:41.260 --> 00:41:43.540
it was because of the culture?

00:41:43.540 --> 00:41:47.810
Or are there other things beyond
just the numbers that you try

00:41:47.810 --> 00:41:50.500
and study to identify
whether this is a culture you

00:41:50.500 --> 00:41:52.120
want to be associated with?

00:41:52.120 --> 00:41:53.911
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Well,
there's many things.

00:41:53.911 --> 00:41:56.830
It's really, what's the
nature of the products, what's

00:41:56.830 --> 00:41:58.030
the nature--

00:41:58.030 --> 00:42:00.880
you know, the funny
thing with Google,

00:42:00.880 --> 00:42:03.760
it was not the
first company that

00:42:03.760 --> 00:42:05.450
had a search engine
on the internet.

00:42:05.450 --> 00:42:05.760
SPEAKER 1: Right.

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:07.801
FRANCOIS ROCHON: It was
the last one that come up

00:42:07.801 --> 00:42:09.670
with a new search engine.

00:42:09.670 --> 00:42:12.190
But this one was
better than the others,

00:42:12.190 --> 00:42:15.860
thinking Yahoo, or
AltaVista, or Excite, Lycos,

00:42:15.860 --> 00:42:18.940
all those first companies
that had search engines.

00:42:18.940 --> 00:42:22.350
So sometimes, it's
the first arrival.

00:42:22.350 --> 00:42:24.990
And sometimes, strangely,
it's the last arrival.

00:42:24.990 --> 00:42:32.000
So that's a tough
thing with investing.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:34.310
Every story is
new and different.

00:42:34.310 --> 00:42:35.580
So you have to--

00:42:35.580 --> 00:42:38.060
when I said it's important
to have an open mind,

00:42:38.060 --> 00:42:42.170
it's because if you have
this very strict frame

00:42:42.170 --> 00:42:44.870
to analyze companies, probably,
you miss lots of things.

00:42:44.870 --> 00:42:46.880
Because every situation is new.

00:42:46.880 --> 00:42:50.360
And the future is all the
world's uncharted territory.

00:42:50.360 --> 00:42:54.080
So you have to have
some principles.

00:42:54.080 --> 00:42:56.300
You look for certain things.

00:42:56.300 --> 00:43:01.220
But in the end, you have
to judge every situation

00:43:01.220 --> 00:43:04.120
differently and by
their own parameters.

00:43:04.120 --> 00:43:06.680
And if you look
at our portfolio,

00:43:06.680 --> 00:43:08.460
we own something
like 25 companies.

00:43:08.460 --> 00:43:14.480
And I think the reasons
we invested in those 25

00:43:14.480 --> 00:43:16.170
differ very much from
one to the other.

00:43:16.170 --> 00:43:18.170
Sometimes it's really
because of the management.

00:43:18.170 --> 00:43:21.950
Sometimes it's really because we
think the brand is very solid.

00:43:21.950 --> 00:43:24.500
And sometimes we
think the company has

00:43:24.500 --> 00:43:27.500
lots of room to grow, and
it's just like a Starbucks,

00:43:27.500 --> 00:43:31.572
where they just have to
clone the concept that they

00:43:31.572 --> 00:43:37.850
have built. So
there's no one recipe.

00:43:37.850 --> 00:43:39.850
It's really to have
an adaptive mind

00:43:39.850 --> 00:43:42.440
and trying to understand
the nature of the business

00:43:42.440 --> 00:43:44.052
you want to invest into it.

00:43:44.052 --> 00:43:46.010
SPEAKER 1: So that leads
into my next question,

00:43:46.010 --> 00:43:48.850
actually, which is, when
do you decide to sell?

00:43:48.850 --> 00:43:52.310
Your said your average holding
period is about seven years,

00:43:52.310 --> 00:43:54.300
and you invest in
quality companies.

00:43:54.300 --> 00:43:56.420
And you know, you gave
the example of CarMax,

00:43:56.420 --> 00:44:00.230
which you have been holding
on for several years.

00:44:00.230 --> 00:44:02.734
But you sold a company like
Intel, if I remember correctly.

00:44:02.734 --> 00:44:03.650
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Yeah.

00:44:03.650 --> 00:44:05.316
SPEAKER 1: So can you
talk about how you

00:44:05.316 --> 00:44:07.100
think about selling companies?

00:44:07.100 --> 00:44:09.300
Because you think of
yourself as a partner.

00:44:09.300 --> 00:44:12.372
So it must be an emotional
process as well maybe.

00:44:12.372 --> 00:44:14.330
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Yeah,
we try to remove emotion

00:44:14.330 --> 00:44:15.350
from the process.

00:44:15.350 --> 00:44:18.780
But it's never easy,
because we're human beings.

00:44:18.780 --> 00:44:19.940
So we're emotional.

00:44:19.940 --> 00:44:21.120
So we have to accept that.

00:44:21.120 --> 00:44:25.010
And sometimes accepting
it and going beyond,

00:44:25.010 --> 00:44:30.390
well, that's why we have
those rules or processes that

00:44:30.390 --> 00:44:31.560
helps to make a decision.

00:44:31.560 --> 00:44:34.960
And there's really four
reasons we'll sell a stock.

00:44:34.960 --> 00:44:36.960
The first one-- if we
realize we made a mistake.

00:44:36.960 --> 00:44:37.990
And that happened.

00:44:37.990 --> 00:44:40.090
And I don't know the ratio.

00:44:40.090 --> 00:44:44.040
It's probably one out of three
or four stocks that we buy,

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:46.440
for some reason,
we've made a mistake.

00:44:46.440 --> 00:44:48.960
And the thing to
do is just sell.

00:44:48.960 --> 00:44:50.820
Accept that it's
part of the process,

00:44:50.820 --> 00:44:56.430
and you're a human being,
and it's a tough world.

00:44:56.430 --> 00:44:59.370
So when you've made a
mistake, you just sell and go

00:44:59.370 --> 00:45:01.546
into some other investment.

00:45:01.546 --> 00:45:03.420
The second reason-- it's
a little different--

00:45:03.420 --> 00:45:05.970
is that you didn't
really make a mistake,

00:45:05.970 --> 00:45:08.846
but the nature of the
business has changed.

00:45:08.846 --> 00:45:10.220
There's a new
competitor, there's

00:45:10.220 --> 00:45:14.540
a new economic environment,
there's new technology.

00:45:14.540 --> 00:45:18.480
Whatever has changed in the
industry or the company itself,

00:45:18.480 --> 00:45:21.310
it's not as great as when
you first purchased it.

00:45:21.310 --> 00:45:23.580
So when you realize
that, you have to sell.

00:45:23.580 --> 00:45:25.620
And it can be a year
after you bought it

00:45:25.620 --> 00:45:27.950
or 10 years after you bought it.

00:45:27.950 --> 00:45:32.590
The third one is probably
when I look at this situation

00:45:32.590 --> 00:45:36.000
and I don't agree with
a management decision.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:38.730
Usually, it's a big acquisition.

00:45:38.730 --> 00:45:41.910
And when I feel that I
don't agree with management,

00:45:41.910 --> 00:45:43.500
I just sell.

00:45:43.500 --> 00:45:46.650
I mean, I have this
saying that if I

00:45:46.650 --> 00:45:50.850
had to resume, in one
sentence, what investing is,

00:45:50.850 --> 00:45:54.600
it's you become partner
with the top management.

00:45:54.600 --> 00:45:56.310
If you don't trust
them anymore, there's

00:45:56.310 --> 00:45:57.670
no reason to be a partner.

00:45:57.670 --> 00:45:59.010
So we sell.

00:45:59.010 --> 00:46:01.770
And the fourth reason, which is
probably the most common one,

00:46:01.770 --> 00:46:05.770
we just found an investment that
we think has better prospects.

00:46:05.770 --> 00:46:09.250
And so we sell A to buy B, not
necessarily because there's

00:46:09.250 --> 00:46:11.520
a problem with A. But
it's just that we think

00:46:11.520 --> 00:46:14.367
that B will be more rewarding.

00:46:14.367 --> 00:46:14.950
SPEAKER 1: OK.

00:46:14.950 --> 00:46:17.050
And finally, before we let
it out to the audience,

00:46:17.050 --> 00:46:20.710
I want to talk about my favorite
part of your annual letters,

00:46:20.710 --> 00:46:23.260
which is those medals.

00:46:23.260 --> 00:46:25.210
And correct me if my
memory is failing me,

00:46:25.210 --> 00:46:27.304
but was Valeant
one of the metals?

00:46:27.304 --> 00:46:28.220
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Yeah.

00:46:28.220 --> 00:46:28.480
Yeah.

00:46:28.480 --> 00:46:30.100
It was a-- yeah,
it was a mistake.

00:46:30.100 --> 00:46:32.200
We were lucky, because
we did make money

00:46:32.200 --> 00:46:33.440
with that investment.

00:46:33.440 --> 00:46:35.060
But it turned out
to be a mistake.

00:46:35.060 --> 00:46:37.930
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, so can
you talk to the audience,

00:46:37.930 --> 00:46:39.760
explain the medals
a little bit more,

00:46:39.760 --> 00:46:43.060
and tell us how you give a
medal, even to something you

00:46:43.060 --> 00:46:45.490
call a mistake, and still
make money out of it?

00:46:45.490 --> 00:46:47.200
FRANCOIS ROCHON:
Well, I would say

00:46:47.200 --> 00:46:51.280
there's a difference between
being good and lucky.

00:46:51.280 --> 00:46:52.520
So we were lucky there.

00:46:52.520 --> 00:46:54.720
So that was still a mistake.

00:46:54.720 --> 00:46:58.960
Basically, well, we
make many mistakes.

00:46:58.960 --> 00:47:03.070
And we only choose to
three to give medals to,

00:47:03.070 --> 00:47:04.690
bronze, silver, and gold.

00:47:04.690 --> 00:47:09.630
And most of the time, the
mistakes our omissions.

00:47:09.630 --> 00:47:12.160
Starbucks is an example
as a company that

00:47:12.160 --> 00:47:14.590
fits all our criteria,
and we decided

00:47:14.590 --> 00:47:19.120
not to buy for, sometimes,
a simplistic reason.

00:47:19.120 --> 00:47:23.320
And you miss, you
know, a 10,000% gain

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:25.480
over 25 years for that reason.

00:47:25.480 --> 00:47:31.450
So we try to give medals to
the most costly mistakes.

00:47:31.450 --> 00:47:34.420
And the most costly
are usually omissions.

00:47:34.420 --> 00:47:36.480
Sometimes it's like Valeant.

00:47:36.480 --> 00:47:38.850
That was a stock
that we did purchase.

00:47:38.850 --> 00:47:41.820
And we made a mistake.

00:47:41.820 --> 00:47:44.320
Well, in the case
of Valeant, I think

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:46.630
we have a lot of confidence
in the management.

00:47:46.630 --> 00:47:50.080
And also, at the same time,
they had much more debt

00:47:50.080 --> 00:47:53.350
than we were usually
willing to live with.

00:47:53.350 --> 00:47:58.220
And we did kind of an
exception to our rules.

00:47:58.220 --> 00:48:00.980
And it turned out
that it was a mistake.

00:48:00.980 --> 00:48:01.930
So--

00:48:01.930 --> 00:48:05.890
SPEAKER 1: But you got out way
before a lot of the other--

00:48:05.890 --> 00:48:08.960
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Yeah, but
the selection was a mistake.

00:48:08.960 --> 00:48:14.090
So it turned out, in the
end, financially, it was OK.

00:48:14.090 --> 00:48:16.570
But that's still a mistake.

00:48:16.570 --> 00:48:18.060
And that's the hard part.

00:48:18.060 --> 00:48:21.280
When you look at your mistakes,
you want to be very objective

00:48:21.280 --> 00:48:24.040
and say, well, this is a
mistake for those reasons.

00:48:24.040 --> 00:48:27.790
But some stocks that I
didn't purchase that went up

00:48:27.790 --> 00:48:31.184
100 times, but I really
didn't understand,

00:48:31.184 --> 00:48:32.350
that's not really a mistake.

00:48:32.350 --> 00:48:34.870
It's just that you
decided that this

00:48:34.870 --> 00:48:37.690
was outside your circle of
competence, and you missed it.

00:48:37.690 --> 00:48:39.490
But that's not really a mistake.

00:48:39.490 --> 00:48:42.220
It's a mistake when it was
in your circle of competence,

00:48:42.220 --> 00:48:45.820
and for some reason, you didn't
go through with the purchase.

00:48:45.820 --> 00:48:48.010
Or it's a mistake
when you thought

00:48:48.010 --> 00:48:50.180
that the company was in
your circle of competence,

00:48:50.180 --> 00:48:51.910
and in the end, it was not.

00:48:51.910 --> 00:48:54.830
So that's basically
the two reasons

00:48:54.830 --> 00:48:59.440
a mistake will be in the
chapter of the annual letter.

00:48:59.440 --> 00:49:02.410
SPEAKER 1: It's interesting
you separate luck and outcome,

00:49:02.410 --> 00:49:05.320
which is what one of
our previous speakers,

00:49:05.320 --> 00:49:08.630
Michael Mauboussin, talks
about, you know, skill and luck.

00:49:08.630 --> 00:49:11.406
And then, Howard Marks
also says that, you

00:49:11.406 --> 00:49:13.480
know-- when he was
here, he said, you know,

00:49:13.480 --> 00:49:16.210
what will happen might
be different from what

00:49:16.210 --> 00:49:17.000
should happen.

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:19.975
So you need to decouple
them in your thinking.

00:49:19.975 --> 00:49:21.100
But thank you very much.

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:22.990
With that, let me open
it up to the audience

00:49:22.990 --> 00:49:27.535
if we have any
questions for you, OK?

00:49:27.535 --> 00:49:29.030
Folks, any questions
for Francois?

00:49:29.030 --> 00:49:30.172
Yeah?

00:49:30.172 --> 00:49:31.130
AUDIENCE: Hi, Francois.

00:49:31.130 --> 00:49:32.040
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Hi.

00:49:32.040 --> 00:49:33.670
AUDIENCE: Thank you
for the excellent talk.

00:49:33.670 --> 00:49:34.560
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Thank you.

00:49:34.560 --> 00:49:36.893
AUDIENCE: I've been reading
your letters over the years,

00:49:36.893 --> 00:49:38.060
and it's really excellent.

00:49:38.060 --> 00:49:39.726
One of the questions
I wanted to ask you

00:49:39.726 --> 00:49:42.980
was, you were showing us
this chart about Walt Disney

00:49:42.980 --> 00:49:45.780
and buying it at 24
times earnings, right?

00:49:45.780 --> 00:49:47.790
How do you pay up
for good businesses?

00:49:47.790 --> 00:49:50.760
Because the times when
these businesses are

00:49:50.760 --> 00:49:53.460
available with this
margin of safety

00:49:53.460 --> 00:49:55.680
is maybe when something
is wrong, maybe

00:49:55.680 --> 00:49:58.780
when the market rightly or
wrongly thinks that something

00:49:58.780 --> 00:50:00.155
is off.

00:50:00.155 --> 00:50:02.280
And if that's not the case,
then how do you pay up?

00:50:02.280 --> 00:50:05.100
But if that's the case, how do
you separate what the market is

00:50:05.100 --> 00:50:08.040
thinking versus reality?

00:50:08.040 --> 00:50:10.800
FRANCOIS ROCHON: We try to
focus on the very long term.

00:50:10.800 --> 00:50:15.030
So we try to look five
years in the future.

00:50:15.030 --> 00:50:19.410
And we come up with
our best judgment,

00:50:19.410 --> 00:50:23.430
what we believe the earnings per
share should be in five years.

00:50:23.430 --> 00:50:28.270
So let's say, Disney,
when we bought in 2005,

00:50:28.270 --> 00:50:31.450
we said, well, we think this
company can earn $3 a share

00:50:31.450 --> 00:50:32.670
in five years.

00:50:32.670 --> 00:50:37.650
And then, if you think that
the fundamentals will still

00:50:37.650 --> 00:50:41.010
be good past those five
years, we say, well,

00:50:41.010 --> 00:50:46.360
it probably will warrant a P/E
ratio of, let's say, 20 times.

00:50:46.360 --> 00:50:49.630
So that gives you a $60
stock in five years.

00:50:49.630 --> 00:50:54.090
So if you can buy the
stock at $30 or less today,

00:50:54.090 --> 00:50:57.320
and you're right on
the $60 in five years,

00:50:57.320 --> 00:51:03.000
you should be rewarded earnings
something like 15% annually.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:07.200
The earnings that
the company has today

00:51:07.200 --> 00:51:09.030
is not really relevant to that.

00:51:09.030 --> 00:51:13.080
So if they earn $1
this year, it looks

00:51:13.080 --> 00:51:14.650
a little pricey at 30 times.

00:51:14.650 --> 00:51:18.030
But if you have a long-term
horizon and you're focusing

00:51:18.030 --> 00:51:19.680
on where the stock will be--

00:51:19.680 --> 00:51:24.089
or the earnings will be--
in five years, in the end,

00:51:24.089 --> 00:51:24.630
you'll be OK.

00:51:24.630 --> 00:51:28.170
So having this long-term
horizon, I believe,

00:51:28.170 --> 00:51:32.620
helps you to defocus on
the P/E ratio of today.

00:51:32.620 --> 00:51:34.180
And it goes the other way.

00:51:34.180 --> 00:51:36.600
If you find a cheap
stock, but you

00:51:36.600 --> 00:51:40.500
look five years in the future
and you don't see any growth

00:51:40.500 --> 00:51:43.169
prospects, there's
no real reason

00:51:43.169 --> 00:51:45.460
to believe that the stock
will be higher in five years.

00:51:45.460 --> 00:51:47.700
It can be higher in three
months just because the P/E

00:51:47.700 --> 00:51:49.070
has gone from 10 to 12 times.

00:51:49.070 --> 00:51:51.770
But we don't try to
invest for three months,

00:51:51.770 --> 00:51:54.437
we try and invest for
at least five years.

00:51:54.437 --> 00:51:55.431
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:51:59.705 --> 00:52:01.830
AUDIENCE: I thank you very
much for the great talk.

00:52:01.830 --> 00:52:03.120
And welcome to Google.

00:52:03.120 --> 00:52:04.120
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Thanks.

00:52:04.120 --> 00:52:05.680
AUDIENCE: So I have a question.

00:52:05.680 --> 00:52:08.300
Considering, now, the
current market conditions,

00:52:08.300 --> 00:52:12.090
there's a lot of warning
by people about the risk.

00:52:12.090 --> 00:52:15.480
And there are a lot of fund
managers returning funds

00:52:15.480 --> 00:52:17.490
to the investors.

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:22.180
So I wonder, what do you think
about the market in general?

00:52:22.180 --> 00:52:25.420
And what's the risk and the
expected return for the, maybe,

00:52:25.420 --> 00:52:26.550
next five, 10 years?

00:52:26.550 --> 00:52:27.530
Thank you.

00:52:27.530 --> 00:52:30.510
FRANCOIS ROCHON:
Yeah, well, of course

00:52:30.510 --> 00:52:34.350
it's not as exciting for an
investor today as it was,

00:52:34.350 --> 00:52:37.980
let's say, in 2009, when stocks
were really, really cheap.

00:52:37.980 --> 00:52:39.600
But you know, it
was scary then too.

00:52:39.600 --> 00:52:45.360
So I always try
to kind of defocus

00:52:45.360 --> 00:52:48.540
what's happening to the market
and more focus on the companies

00:52:48.540 --> 00:52:51.000
that we own in the portfolio.

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:53.100
And when we look
at our portfolio,

00:52:53.100 --> 00:52:56.760
and we've got this group
of 25 companies that,

00:52:56.760 --> 00:52:58.740
we're pretty
confident that they'll

00:52:58.740 --> 00:53:01.560
grow their earnings
by at least 10% to 12%

00:53:01.560 --> 00:53:04.230
in the next five years,
and their P/E ratio,

00:53:04.230 --> 00:53:09.864
seems reasonable, there's no
reason, I think, to be worried.

00:53:09.864 --> 00:53:12.030
I don't know what the market
will do in the next six

00:53:12.030 --> 00:53:13.975
months, a year, or two.

00:53:13.975 --> 00:53:16.350
But I think the companies we
own, in the next five years,

00:53:16.350 --> 00:53:18.140
will do OK.

00:53:18.140 --> 00:53:20.210
And if you look at the
general stock market,

00:53:20.210 --> 00:53:22.340
we don't have views in general.

00:53:22.340 --> 00:53:25.010
But we think that
companies can continue

00:53:25.010 --> 00:53:28.640
to grow their earnings per
share at, say, 5% to 7%

00:53:28.640 --> 00:53:30.950
annually in the next five years.

00:53:30.950 --> 00:53:33.540
And you add a dividend to 2%.

00:53:33.540 --> 00:53:37.310
So even though there's no P/E
changes over the next five

00:53:37.310 --> 00:53:41.120
years, well, that would
translate into a total return,

00:53:41.120 --> 00:53:43.980
for stocks, from 7% to 9%.

00:53:43.980 --> 00:53:47.570
So it's not as exciting
as eight years ago.

00:53:47.570 --> 00:53:51.675
But still, it's pretty decent
returns when you compare that

00:53:51.675 --> 00:53:54.760
to bonds, which probably yield
something like less than 2%

00:53:54.760 --> 00:53:56.830
over the next five years.

00:53:56.830 --> 00:54:02.190
So it's not extraordinary
exciting to find opportunities.

00:54:02.190 --> 00:54:05.760
But I think the returns will be
decent, mostly for the stocks

00:54:05.760 --> 00:54:09.077
we own, and probably the
stock market as well.

00:54:09.077 --> 00:54:09.910
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:54:09.910 --> 00:54:11.701
SPEAKER 1: We have one
question over there.

00:54:15.321 --> 00:54:16.570
AUDIENCE: Thanks for the talk.

00:54:16.570 --> 00:54:18.080
I actually have a
couple of questions.

00:54:18.080 --> 00:54:19.520
The first one is,
I was just look--

00:54:19.520 --> 00:54:21.061
I don't know if it's
accurate or not.

00:54:21.061 --> 00:54:22.830
I was just looking
at your holdings.

00:54:22.830 --> 00:54:25.810
And I noticed you have
