00:54:40.296 --> 00:54:43.320
Because they seem to
track each other anyways.

00:54:43.320 --> 00:54:44.660
So that's the first question.

00:54:44.660 --> 00:54:46.870
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Yeah,
well, that's a very easy--

00:54:46.870 --> 00:54:49.150
we prefer Visa, obviously.

00:54:49.150 --> 00:54:51.890
And MasterCard, we own a few
shares just to follow it.

00:54:51.890 --> 00:54:54.830
But we think both
companies are great.

00:54:54.830 --> 00:54:56.850
These are fantastic businesses.

00:54:56.850 --> 00:54:58.510
We prefer Visa.

00:54:58.510 --> 00:55:00.740
And MasterCard, just
to follow the company,

00:55:00.740 --> 00:55:02.590
we have a few shares.

00:55:02.590 --> 00:55:04.739
SPEAKER 1: Is that
because of Visa Europe?

00:55:04.739 --> 00:55:06.280
FRANCOIS ROCHON:
No, just in general,

00:55:06.280 --> 00:55:09.700
I think Visa is an
extraordinary business.

00:55:09.700 --> 00:55:15.330
And I think it's hard to
say, because MasterCard

00:55:15.330 --> 00:55:16.380
is a great business too.

00:55:16.380 --> 00:55:20.225
But I think Visa has a
little something more.

00:55:20.225 --> 00:55:21.600
AUDIENCE: And the
second question

00:55:21.600 --> 00:55:24.210
is, in terms of the
big tech stocks,

00:55:24.210 --> 00:55:27.110
right, I noticed
you have Google.

00:55:27.110 --> 00:55:28.530
So thank you.

00:55:28.530 --> 00:55:29.780
But just curious--

00:55:29.780 --> 00:55:31.740
FRANCOIS ROCHON:
Well, thank you.

00:55:31.740 --> 00:55:34.365
AUDIENCE: I was wondering if you
could maybe give your thoughts

00:55:34.365 --> 00:55:35.790
on Apple, why you don't own it.

00:55:35.790 --> 00:55:39.152
Because I mean, personally,
I own a position in it,

00:55:39.152 --> 00:55:40.860
because I think it's
got a low valuation.

00:55:40.860 --> 00:55:43.350
And it's got a very
good moat around it,

00:55:43.350 --> 00:55:45.940
especially with all the
services added to it.

00:55:45.940 --> 00:55:47.746
So just curious on
your thoughts on that.

00:55:47.746 --> 00:55:49.620
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Yeah,
well, obviously, Apple

00:55:49.620 --> 00:55:53.810
could be in the section of
mistakes, because I mean,

00:55:53.810 --> 00:55:56.160
it's up, what, 50 times
in the last decade

00:55:56.160 --> 00:55:57.370
or something like that.

00:55:57.370 --> 00:55:59.100
So it's been a great investment.

00:55:59.100 --> 00:56:00.107
It's a great company.

00:56:00.107 --> 00:56:01.440
I mean, I can't argue with that.

00:56:01.440 --> 00:56:04.410
And the valuation
does look very low.

00:56:04.410 --> 00:56:06.690
And I think they do have a moat.

00:56:06.690 --> 00:56:10.470
And probably, five years
ago, I wasn't that convinced

00:56:10.470 --> 00:56:13.320
that the moat was that large.

00:56:13.320 --> 00:56:16.565
And it turned out that it
is a very solid business.

00:56:19.110 --> 00:56:19.950
And I think--

00:56:19.950 --> 00:56:21.840
I don't know exactly
the number, but I think,

00:56:21.840 --> 00:56:26.600
today, 10% of their revenues
are service-based and recurring.

00:56:26.600 --> 00:56:29.820
And as it get a larger
part of their revenues,

00:56:29.820 --> 00:56:32.460
I think that moat
will be expanding.

00:56:32.460 --> 00:56:36.150
Still, a large part of
their revenues and earnings

00:56:36.150 --> 00:56:38.640
come from selling new products.

00:56:38.640 --> 00:56:42.240
And when you have to sell
something new every two

00:56:42.240 --> 00:56:47.790
or three years, there's a risk
that you'll miss a product

00:56:47.790 --> 00:56:49.860
launch, or something
will not exactly

00:56:49.860 --> 00:56:51.870
satisfy the customer
for whatever reason.

00:56:51.870 --> 00:56:54.390
Or you just have the
risk, also, of having

00:56:54.390 --> 00:56:56.910
another company that comes
up with a new and improved

00:56:56.910 --> 00:56:57.940
product.

00:56:57.940 --> 00:57:00.550
So I think, if you
compare Apple and Google,

00:57:00.550 --> 00:57:03.930
I think, Google's business
is more stable, and more

00:57:03.930 --> 00:57:07.670
entrenched, and more recurring.

00:57:07.670 --> 00:57:10.950
And I think the moat is
larger in Google than Apple.

00:57:10.950 --> 00:57:12.950
That doesn't mean Apple
is not a great business.

00:57:12.950 --> 00:57:15.590
And you have to ask yourself--

00:57:15.590 --> 00:57:19.570
at that price, the P/E
ratio difference is so high.

00:57:19.570 --> 00:57:21.950
I think Apple
trades at 15 times,

00:57:21.950 --> 00:57:23.840
and Google is probably 25 times.

00:57:23.840 --> 00:57:25.206
SPEAKER 1: What about Visa?

00:57:25.206 --> 00:57:26.850
FRANCOIS ROCHON:
Visa is close to 30.

00:57:26.850 --> 00:57:29.717
SPEAKER 1: So isn't'
that too high?

00:57:29.717 --> 00:57:31.800
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Well, I
remember, many years ago,

00:57:31.800 --> 00:57:35.030
Philip Fisher wrote,
in his book that--

00:57:35.030 --> 00:57:37.410
"Common Stocks and
Uncommon Profits"--

00:57:37.410 --> 00:57:40.900
the further in the future
you can see growth,

00:57:40.900 --> 00:57:43.440
the higher the P/E
ratio you can pay.

00:57:43.440 --> 00:57:46.620
So in terms of Visa,
I think you can

00:57:46.620 --> 00:57:52.770
see the company having the most
protected for many, many years.

00:57:52.770 --> 00:57:55.870
It's hard to figure out
who could hurt them.

00:57:55.870 --> 00:57:58.990
And you can see many,
many years of growth.

00:57:58.990 --> 00:58:02.220
So I think that warrants
a high P/E ratio.

00:58:02.220 --> 00:58:06.900
But of course, it was better
in 2010 when we bought it.

00:58:06.900 --> 00:58:09.840
I think we paid, I don't
know, 15 times earnings.

00:58:09.840 --> 00:58:13.530
So obviously, we had a much
larger margin of safety then

00:58:13.530 --> 00:58:15.304
than we have today.

00:58:15.304 --> 00:58:16.470
AUDIENCE: I've got one more.

00:58:16.470 --> 00:58:17.920
FRANCOIS ROCHON: I don't know
if that answers your question.

00:58:17.920 --> 00:58:18.340
AUDIENCE: Yeah it does.

00:58:18.340 --> 00:58:19.070
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, go ahead.

00:58:19.070 --> 00:58:20.820
AUDIENCE: Maybe--
because I noticed

00:58:20.820 --> 00:58:24.390
one of your largest holdings
is Berkshire Hathaway as well.

00:58:24.390 --> 00:58:26.275
And they've taken a
big position in Apple.

00:58:26.275 --> 00:58:27.150
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Yeah

00:58:27.150 --> 00:58:28.590
AUDIENCE: So
indirectly, you actually

00:58:28.590 --> 00:58:30.690
probably own more shares of
Apple through your holdings--

00:58:30.690 --> 00:58:30.990
FRANCOIS ROCHON: There you go.

00:58:30.990 --> 00:58:32.010
AUDIENCE: --of Berkshire
Hathaway than Apple.

00:58:32.010 --> 00:58:34.620
I don't know if you look
into that, that, you know,

00:58:34.620 --> 00:58:35.520
I own this company.

00:58:35.520 --> 00:58:36.900
And it already
gives me exposure.

00:58:36.900 --> 00:58:38.040
So I won't own it separately.

00:58:38.040 --> 00:58:39.090
Do you think about that?

00:58:39.090 --> 00:58:43.200
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Well,
that's not really a reason.

00:58:43.200 --> 00:58:45.645
Of course, when we own
Berkshire, we own Apple,

00:58:45.645 --> 00:58:50.700
and we own Coca-Cola, and we
own Geico, and some Burlington

00:58:50.700 --> 00:58:53.790
Northern Santa Fe, and
Precision Castparts.

00:58:53.790 --> 00:58:57.690
And BNSF and Precision
Castparts was in the portfolio

00:58:57.690 --> 00:58:58.530
a few years back.

00:58:58.530 --> 00:59:02.330
So we're still shareholders.

00:59:02.330 --> 00:59:04.380
But you know, if we
thought that Apple

00:59:04.380 --> 00:59:08.820
was a good purchase for
us today, owning Berkshire

00:59:08.820 --> 00:59:10.729
wouldn't be a
reason not to do it.

00:59:10.729 --> 00:59:12.270
SPEAKER 1: So
Francois, when you look

00:59:12.270 --> 00:59:16.200
at something like Visa
or Apple, your portfolio

00:59:16.200 --> 00:59:17.310
has low-debt companies.

00:59:17.310 --> 00:59:20.340
Sometimes they might
even have excess cash.

00:59:20.340 --> 00:59:22.170
So when you look
at the P/E ratio,

00:59:22.170 --> 00:59:23.760
do you take the cash out?

00:59:23.760 --> 00:59:24.450
How do you--

00:59:24.450 --> 00:59:26.700
FRANCOIS ROCHON: Yeah, you
should do that, I think so.

00:59:26.700 --> 00:59:31.080
Because I mean, that's cash that
could be returned to investors.

00:59:31.080 --> 00:59:33.390
It's a little harder
for Apple or Google,

00:59:33.390 --> 00:59:37.020
because a lot of those
cash is in other countries.

00:59:37.020 --> 00:59:39.540
Sometimes a little
complicated to get back

00:59:39.540 --> 00:59:42.190
in the US, the cash, and
give it to shareholders.

00:59:42.190 --> 00:59:45.470
But in the end, in
some way or the other,

00:59:45.470 --> 00:59:48.420
this cash will be
returned to shareholders,

00:59:48.420 --> 00:59:52.230
I hope, and should be
taken out of the valuation.

00:59:52.230 --> 00:59:54.450
But what you want
to do is really do

00:59:54.450 --> 00:59:58.350
the sum of what you
expect the cash to be

00:59:58.350 --> 01:00:02.250
generated by the company in
the future discounted to today.

01:00:02.250 --> 01:00:04.540
And then you add the
cash that is today.

01:00:04.540 --> 01:00:06.242
So you get a proper valuation.

01:00:06.242 --> 01:00:06.950
SPEAKER 1: Right.

01:00:06.950 --> 01:00:08.220
Well, it makes sense.

01:00:08.220 --> 01:00:11.441
With that, Francois, thank you
so much for being with us here

01:00:11.441 --> 01:00:11.940
today.

